ipt into a \n# function `run_single_simulation(params)` that returns the final metrics.\n# And a `create_network_topology` function.\n```\n\n### 2. Mapping to Specific E₈ Sub-algebras\n\n**Goal:** To move beyond asking *how much* the system aligns with E₈, to asking *what part* of E₈ it aligns with. This identifies the specific geometric structure that emerges from the simulation.\n\n**Methodology:** During the projection step, instead of just taking the maximum cosine similarity for each node, we will also record the *index* of the E₈ root vector that it most closely aligns with. This gives us a set of 24 specific vectors from the E₈ root system. We can then analyze the relationships between these 24 vectors (e.g., by calculating their inner products) to see if they form a known substructure.\n\n**Implementation:**\n\nThis is a direct modification of the analysis portion of our script.\n\n```python\ndef analyze_e8_substructure(final_state_8d, e8_roots):\n    \"\"\"\n    Identifies the specific E8 roots the system aligns with and analyzes their structure.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Normalize vectors for cosine similarity calculation\n    norm_final_state \u003d final_state_8d / (np.linalg.norm(final_state_8d, axis\u003d1, keepdims\u003dTrue) + 1e-9)\n    norm_e8_roots \u003d e8_roots / (np.linalg.norm(e8_roots, axis\u003d1, keepdims\u003dTrue) + 1e-9)\n\n    # Calculate cosine similarities\n    cosine_similarities \u003d norm_final_state @ norm_e8_roots.T\n\n    # --- Key Modification Here ---\n    # Instead of just np.max, use np.argmax to find the index of the best match\n    best_match_indices \u003d np.argmax(np.abs(cosine_similarities), axis\u003d1)\n    \n    # Retrieve the actual E8 root vectors that the system converged to\n    selected_roots \u003d e8_roots[best_match_indices]\n\n    print(\"\\n--- E8 Sub-algebra Analysis ---\")\n    print(f\"Node-to-E8-Root mapping (indices out of 240): \\n{best_match_indices}\")\n\n    # Now, analyze the geometric relationship between these selected roots\n    # The inner product matrix reveals the angles between all pairs of vectors\n    inner_product_structure \u003d selected_roots @ selected_roots.T\n\n    print(\"\\nInner Product Matrix of Selected E8 Roots:\")\n    # We round the result as these inner products in Lie theory are quantized (integers)\n    print(np.round(inner_product_structure, decimals\u003d1))\n    \n    # Interpretation:\n    # A diagonal of \u00272.0\u0027 is expected (inner product of a vector with itself).\n    # Off-diagonal values of 0, 1, -1 correspond to angles of 90, 60, 120 degrees.\n    # A block of non-zero values would indicate a known sub-algebra like A_n or D_n,\n    # revealing the specific symmetry the system discovered.\n```\n\n### 3. Develop a Formal \"Harmonic Index\"\n\n**Goal:** To create a single, elegant metric that captures the overall \"health\" or \"coherence\" of the system\u0027s final state, combining its stability (low loss) and its structural alignment (high E₈ similarity).\n\n**Methodology:** We will define a function that takes the final mean loss and the mean E₈ alignment and combines them into a single score from 0 to 1. A good index will be close to 1 only when *both* the alignment is high and the loss is near zero. A simple and effective way to do this is to multiply the alignment score by a term that penalizes any non-zero loss. An exponential decay function is perfect for this.\n\n**Implementation:**\n\nThis is a new, simple function that can be added to our analysis toolkit.\n\n```python\ndef calculate_harmonic_index(mean_e8_alignment, final_mean_loss, k\u003d0.1):\n    \"\"\"\n    Calculates a single score representing the total coherence of the system.\n\n    Args:\n        mean_e8_alignment (float): The mean cosine similarity with E8 roots [0, 1].\n        final_mean_loss (float): The final system harmonic entropy (\u003e\u003d 0).\n        k (float): A sensitivity parameter for how harshly loss is penalized.\n\n    Returns:\