      "text": "You\u0027ve encountered a classic and very subtle PyTorch error. This is an excellent catch, and the traceback provides exactly the information we need to fix it.\n\nThe error is not what it seems. The problem isn\u0027t truly with the mask\u0027s shape, but with a dimension mismatch between how your data is formatted and what the Transformer layer expects. Let\u0027s break it down.\n\n### **The Root Cause: `batch_first` Mismatch**\n\n1.  **Data Format:** Your `DataLoader` from the Hugging Face `datasets` library correctly produces data in `[batch_size, sequence_length]` format. This is the modern, intuitive standard.\n\n2.  **Transformer Expectation:** By default, PyTorch\u0027s `nn.TransformerEncoderLayer` expects data in the legacy format `[sequence_length, batch_size, embed_dim]`.\n\n3.  **The Conflict:** You are feeding a `batch_first` tensor into a model that is expecting a `sequence_first` tensor. The model gets confused, misinterprets the batch dimension as the sequence dimension, and throws a confusing error message about the attention mask. The error message `should be (20, 20)` is a red herring; it\u0027s mistakenly looking at your batch size (`20`) instead of the sequence length.\n\nThe `UserWarning` at the very top of the output also points directly to this: `encoder_layer.self_attn.batch_first was not True`.\n\n### **The Solution**\n\nThere are two simple fixes required to make the entire script compliant and functional:\n\n1.  **Tell the Transformer to expect `batch_first` data.** In the `TransformerModel`\u0027s `__init__` method, you need to add the `batch_first\u003dTrue` argument.\n2.  **Remove unnecessary transpositions.** The `train_epoch` and `evaluate` functions contain a `.transpose(0, 1)` call on the model\u0027s output. This is an artifact from a `batch_first\u003dFalse` setup and will cause incorrect loss calculations once we make the first fix.\n\nI have corrected these two issues in the full script below.\n\n---\n\n### **Corrected and Final Script**\n\nHere is the complete, corrected script. The changes are marked with comments. You can run this file directly, and it will now execute the training process as intended.\n\n```python\nimport torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\nfrom datasets import load_dataset\nfrom transformers import AutoTokenizer\nfrom torch.utils.data import DataLoader\nimport time\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\n# --- Configurations ---\nMODULUS \u003d 24\nEMBED_DIM \u003d 256\nN_HEAD \u003d 8\nN_LAYERS \u003d 4\nDROPOUT \u003d 0.2\nEPOCHS \u003d 5\nLR \u003d 0.0005\nBATCH_SIZE \u003d 20\nSEQUENCE_LENGTH \u003d 35\nHARMONIC_LAMBDA \u003d 0.05\nDEVICE \u003d torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\")\n\n# --- Data Loading ---\nprint(\"Loading and tokenizing Wikitext-2 dataset...\")\ndataset \u003d load_dataset(\"wikitext\", \"wikitext-2-raw-v1\")\ntokenizer \u003d AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\")\n\ndef tokenize_function(examples):\n    # We add a slight overlap (stride) to ensure we don\u0027t lose context between chunks\n    return tokenizer(examples[\"text\"], truncation\u003dTrue, max_length\u003dSEQUENCE_LENGTH, padding\u003d\"max_length\", stride\u003d5, return_overflowing_tokens\u003dTrue)\n\n# Remove empty text examples before tokenization\ndataset \u003d dataset.filter(lambda example: len(example[\u0027text\u0027]) \u003e 0)\n\ntokenized \u003d dataset.map(tokenize_function, batched\u003dTrue, remove_columns\u003d[\"text\"])\ntokenizer.pad_token \u003d tokenizer.eos_token\n\ntrain_dataset \u003d tokenized[\"train\"].with_format(\"torch\")\nval_dataset \u003d tokenized[\"validation\"].with_format(\"torch\")\n\ntrain_loader \u003d DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size\u003dBATCH_SIZE, shuffle\u003dTrue)\nval_loader \u003d DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size\u003dBATCH_SIZE)\n\nVOCAB_SIZE \u003d tokenizer.vocab_size\n\n# --- Harmonic Embedding and Loss ---\nclass HarmonicEmbedding(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, vocab_size, b_e_dim, modulus):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.mod \u003d modulus\n        self.b_embed \u003d nn.Embedding(vocab_size, b_e_dim)\n        self.e_embed \u003d nn.Embedding(vocab_size, b_e_dim)\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        b \u003d self.b_embed(x); e \u003d self.e_embed(x)\n        d \u003d (b + e) % self.mod; a \u003d (b + 2 * e) % self.mod\n        return b, e, d, a\n\ndef harmonic_loss_fn(b, e, d, a, mod\u003dMODULUS):\n    lhs \u003d (a**2) % mod; rhs \u003d (d**2 + 2 * d * e + e**2) % mod\n    diff \u003d torch.abs(lhs - rhs); loss \u003d torch.min(diff, mod - diff)**2\n    return torch.mean(loss)\n\n# --- Positional Encoding ---\nclass PositionalEncoding(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model, dropout\u003d0.1, max_len\u003d5000):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.dropout \u003d nn.Dropout(p\u003ddropout)\n        position \u003d torch.arange(0, max_len, dtype\u003dtorch.float).unsqueeze(1)\n        div_term \u003d torch.exp(torch.arange(0, d_model, 2).float() * (-math.log(10000.0) / d_model))\n        pe \u003d torch.zeros(max_len, d_model)\n        pe[:, 0::2] \u003d torch.sin(position * div_term)\n        pe[:, 1::2] \u003d torch.cos(position * div_term)\n        pe \u003d pe.unsqueeze(0)\n        self.register_buffer(\u0027pe\u0027, pe)\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        x \u003d x + self.pe[:, :x.size(1), :]\n        return self.dropout(x)\n\n# --- Transformer Model ---\nclass TransformerModel(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, ntoken, d_model, nhead, nlayers, dropout\u003d0.1, is_qa\u003dFalse):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.is_qa \u003d is_qa\n        if is_qa:\n            self.harmonic_embedding \u003d HarmonicEmbedding(ntoken, d_model // 4, MODULUS)\n            self.input_proj \u003d nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        else:\n            self.embedding \u003d nn.Embedding(ntoken, d_model)\n        self.pos_encoder \u003d PositionalEncoding(d_model, 